{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Jrd7h3FRNfh8MvBVPgc2ty","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Cloche Usage\n     2→\n     3→Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\n     4→workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\n     5→container, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\n     6→results to a git branch.\n     7→\n     8→## Core Concepts\n     9→\n    10→- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n    11→- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n    12→- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n    13→- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n    14→- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n    15→\n    16→## Workflow DSL\n    17→\n    18→Workflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\n    19→declared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\n    20→no orphans, entry point exists).\n    21→\n    22→### Minimal Example\n    23→\n    24→```\n    25→workflow \"develop\" {\n    26→  step implement {\n    27→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    28→    results = [success, fail]\n    29→  }\n    30→\n    31→  step test {\n    32→    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    33→    results = [success, fail]\n    34→  }\n    35→\n    36→  implement:success -> test\n    37→  implement:fail -> abort\n    38→  test:success -> done\n    39→  test:fail -> abort\n    40→}\n    41→```\n    42→\n    43→### Step Configuration\n    44→\n    45→| Key | Type | Description |\n    46→|-----|------|-------------|\n    47→| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n    48→| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n    49→| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n    50→| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n    51→| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n    52→| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n    53→| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n    54→| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n    55→| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n    56→| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n    57→\n    58→A step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n    59→\n    60→### The `file()` Function\n    61→\n    62→`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n    63→(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\n    64→templates:\n    65→\n    66→```\n    67→prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    68→```\n    69→\n    70→### The `container {}` Block\n    71→\n    72→Can appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n    73→\n    74→**Step level** — per-step container config:\n    75→```\n    76→step code {\n    77→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    78→  container {\n    79→    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    80→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    81→    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n    82→  }\n    83→  results = [success, fail]\n    84→}\n    85→```\n    86→\n    87→**Workflow level** — defaults for all steps:\n    88→```\n    89→workflow \"develop\" {\n    90→  container {\n    91→    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    92→    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    93→    memory        = \"4g\"\n    94→  }\n    95→  ...\n    96→}\n    97→```\n    98→\n    99→Supported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   100→\n   101→### The `host {}` Block\n   102→\n   103→Can appear at workflow level in host workflows (`.cloche/host.cloche`). Keys are stored\n   104→with a `host.` prefix. Configures agent defaults for agent steps running on the host.\n   105→\n   106→```\n   107→workflow \"main\" {\n   108→  host {\n   109→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   110→  }\n   111→  ...\n   112→}\n   113→```\n   114→\n   115→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   116→`agent_args` config keys override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults.\n   117→\n   118→### Wiring Syntax\n   119→\n   120→Connect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n   121→\n   122→```\n   123→implement:success -> test\n   124→implement:fail -> abort\n   125→test:success -> done\n   126→test:fail -> fix\n   127→```\n   128→\n   129→### Wire Output Mappings\n   130→\n   131→Extract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n   132→\n   133→```\n   134→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135→```\n   136→\n   137→Path expressions:\n   138→\n   139→| Expression | Meaning |\n   140→|---|---|\n   141→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   142→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   143→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   144→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   145→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   146→\n   147→If the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\n   148→text, only bare `output` works.\n   149→\n   150→### Retry Loops\n   151→\n   152→Wire failures back to earlier steps:\n   153→\n   154→```\n   155→test:fail -> fix\n   156→fix:success -> test    // retry the test\n   157→fix:fail -> abort\n   158→```\n   159→\n   160→Use `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n   161→\n   162→```\n   163→step fix {\n   164→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   165→  max_attempts = \"2\"\n   166→  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   167→}\n   168→```\n   169→\n   170→### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n   171→\n   172→Wire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n   173→\n   174→```\n   175→test:success -> lint\n   176→test:success -> quality\n   177→```\n   178→\n   179→### Collect (Join)\n   180→\n   181→Synchronize parallel branches:\n   182→\n   183→```\n   184→collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   185→collect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   186→```\n   187→\n   188→`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n   189→\n   190→### Comments\n   191→\n   192→Line comments with `//`:\n   193→\n   194→```\n   195→// This is a comment\n   196→implement:success -> test  // inline comment\n   197→```\n   198→\n   199→## Result Protocol\n   200→\n   201→Steps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n   202→\n   203→```\n   204→CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n   205→```\n   206→\n   207→For example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n   208→\n   209→Rules:\n   210→- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n   211→- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n   212→- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n   213→- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n   214→- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n   215→\n   216→## Prompt Assembly\n   217→\n   218→When an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n   219→\n   220→1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n   221→2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n   222→3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n   223→4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n   224→\n   225→The assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n   226→\n   227→## Agent Command Resolution\n   228→\n   229→Priority (highest to lowest):\n   230→1. Step-level `agent_command`\n   231→2. Workflow-level config block (`container { agent_command }` for container workflows, `host { agent_command }` for host workflows)\n   232→3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n   233→4. Default: `claude`\n   234→\n   235→### Fallback Chains\n   236→\n   237→Comma-separated commands are tried in order:\n   238→\n   239→```\n   240→agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n   241→```\n   242→\n   243→- **Command not found / failed to start** — try next command\n   244→- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — try next command\n   245→- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n   246→- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n   247→- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n   248→- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n   249→\n   250→Known agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n   251→\n   252→### Agent Setup Guides\n   253→\n   254→For detailed container setup instructions per agent:\n   255→\n   256→- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) — session-based auth, no API key needed\n   257→- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) — API key configuration\n   258→\n   259→## Workflow Locations\n   260→\n   261→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) run inside Docker\n   262→via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type.\n   263→\n   264→**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) runs on the host machine as the daemon.\n   265→Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\n   266→dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes. Script steps\n   267→execute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\n   268→fixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n   269→\n   270→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n   271→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n   272→\n   273→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n   274→|-------|--------------|---------|\n   275→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n   276→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n   277→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n   278→\n   279→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\n   280→mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n   281→\n   282→### list-tasks Output Format\n   283→\n   284→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n   285→object:\n   286→\n   287→| Field | Required | Description |\n   288→|-------|----------|-------------|\n   289→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n   290→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n   291→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n   292→| `description` | no | Full description |\n   293→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n   294→\n   295→The daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\n   296→set in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\n   297→deduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n   298→\n   299→### Host Workflow Example\n   300→\n   301→A three-phase `host.cloche`:\n   302→\n   303→```\n   304→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   305→  step fetch-tickets {\n   306→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   307→    results = [success, fail]\n   308→  }\n   309→\n   310→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   311→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   312→}\n   313→\n   314→workflow \"main\" {\n   315→  host {\n   316→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   317→  }\n   318→\n   319→  step prepare-prompt {\n   320→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   321→    results = [success, fail]\n   322→  }\n   323→\n   324→  step develop {\n   325→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   326→    results       = [success, fail]\n   327→  }\n   328→\n   329→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   330→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   331→  develop:success        -> done\n   332→  develop:fail           -> done\n   333→}\n   334→\n   335→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   336→  step push-for-review {\n   337→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   338→    results = [success, fail]\n   339→  }\n   340→\n   341→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   342→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   343→}\n   344→```\n   345→\n   346→The `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\n   347→receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\n   348→workflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\n   349→what cleanup to perform.\n   350→\n   351→### Host Step Environment Variables\n   352→\n   353→| Variable | Description |\n   354→|----------|-------------|\n   355→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n   356→| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n   357→| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n   358→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   359→| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n   360→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   361→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   362→| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n   363→\n   364→### Container Environment Variables\n   365→\n   366→| Variable | Description |\n   367→|----------|-------------|\n   368→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   369→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n   370→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n   371→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n   372→\n   373→## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n   374→\n   375→```\n   376→workflow \"develop\" {\n   377→  step implement {\n   378→    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n   379→    results = [success, fail]\n   380→  }\n   381→\n   382→  step test {\n   383→    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n   384→    results = [success, fail]\n   385→  }\n   386→\n   387→  step lint {\n   388→    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n   389→    results = [success, fail]\n   390→  }\n   391→\n   392→  step quality {\n   393→    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n   394→    results = [success, fail]\n   395→  }\n   396→\n   397→  step fix {\n   398→    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n   399→    max_attempts = \"2\"\n   400→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   401→  }\n   402→\n   403→  implement:success -> test\n   404→  implement:fail -> abort\n   405→\n   406→  test:success -> lint\n   407→  test:success -> quality\n   408→  test:fail -> fix\n   409→\n   410→  lint:fail -> fix\n   411→  quality:fail -> fix\n   412→  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   413→\n   414→  fix:success -> test\n   415→  fix:fail -> abort\n   416→  fix:give-up -> abort\n   417→}\n   418→```\n   419→\n   420→## Container Isolation Model\n   421→\n   422→- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n   423→- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n   424→- **Auth files**: `~/.claude/` and `~/.claude.json` are copied into each container at `/home/agent/` for Claude Code session reuse. Copied (not bind-mounted) so each container gets its own isolated copy.\n   425→- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n   426→- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n   427→\n   428→Your project directory is never modified by the container.\n   429→\n   430→## CLI Reference\n   431→\n   432→### `cloche init`\n   433→\n   434→Scaffold a new Cloche project.\n   435→\n   436→```\n   437→cloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n   438→```\n   439→\n   440→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   441→|------|---------|-------------|\n   442→| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   443→| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n   444→\n   445→Creates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\n   446→host workflow (`host.cloche`), and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n   447→\n   448→### `cloche run`\n   449→\n   450→Launch a workflow run.\n   451→\n   452→```\n   453→cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n   454→```\n   455→\n   456→| Flag | Description |\n   457→|------|-------------|\n   458→| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   459→| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n   460→| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n   461→| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n   462→\n   463→Must be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\n   464→when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n   465→\n   466→### `cloche status`\n   467→\n   468→```\n   469→cloche status <run-id>\n   470→```\n   471→\n   472→Shows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n   473→\n   474→### `cloche list`\n   475→\n   476→```\n   477→cloche list [--all]\n   478→```\n   479→\n   480→Lists runs for the current project directory. Pass `--all` to show runs across all projects.\n   481→\n   482→### `cloche logs`\n   483→\n   484→```\n   485→cloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [-f]\n   486→```\n   487→\n   488→| Flag | Description |\n   489→|------|-------------|\n   490→| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n   491→| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n   492→| `-f` | Follow mode: display existing logs then continue streaming new lines as they arrive (like `tail -f`). |\n   493→\n   494→Without `-f`, displays all logs captured to date and exits (even for active runs). With `-f` on an active run, existing logs are sent first, then new output is streamed in real time via gRPC until the run completes.\n   495→\n   496→### `cloche poll`\n   497→\n   498→```\n   499→cloche poll <run-id>\n   500→```\n   501→\n   502→Block until the run finishes. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure.\n   503→\n   504→### `cloche stop`\n   505→\n   506→```\n   507→cloche stop <run-id>\n   508→```\n   509→\n   510→### `cloche delete`\n   511→\n   512→```\n   513→cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   514→```\n   515→\n   516→Delete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n   517→\n   518→### `cloche health`\n   519→\n   520→```\n   521→cloche health\n   522→```\n   523→\n   524→Show per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n   525→\n   526→### `cloche get`\n   527→\n   528→```\n   529→cloche get <key>\n   530→```\n   531→\n   532→Get a value from the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   533→the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   534→the current working directory. Exits 1 if the key is not found.\n   535→\n   536→### `cloche set`\n   537→\n   538→```\n   539→cloche set <key> <value|->\n   540→```\n   541→\n   542→Set a value in the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   543→the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   544→the current working directory. Creates the file and directories if they don't exist.\n   545→Pass `-` as the value to read from stdin (trailing newlines are trimmed).\n   546→\n   547→### `cloche tasks`\n   548→\n   549→```\n   550→cloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n   551→```\n   552→\n   553→Show the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\n   554→upcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\n   555→state. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n   556→\n   557→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   558→|------|---------|-------------|\n   559→| `--project <dir>` | current directory name | Project to query tasks for. |\n   560→\n   561→### `cloche shutdown`\n   562→\n   563→```\n   564→cloche shutdown\n   565→```\n   566→\n   567→## Project Layout\n   568→\n   569→```\n   570→my-project/\n   571→├── .cloche/\n   572→│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n   573→│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow\n   574→│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n   575→│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration\n   576→│   ├── prompts/              # Prompt templates\n   577→│   │   ├── implement.md\n   578→│   │   ├── fix.md\n   579→│   │   └── update-docs.md\n   580→│   ├── scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n   581→│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n   582→│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n   583→│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n   584→│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt\n   585→│       ├── context.json      # Shared key-value store (cloche get/set)\n   586→│       ├── output/\n   587→│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified log\n   588→│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n   589→│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n   590→│       ├── attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n   591→│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n   592→├── src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n   593→└── .git/\n   594→```\n   595→\n   596→## Daemon Configuration\n   597→\n   598→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   599→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   600→| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n   601→| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n   602→| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n   603→| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n   604→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n   605→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n   606→| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n   607→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n   608→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n   609→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n   610→\n   611→### Client Configuration\n   612→\n   613→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   614→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   615→| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n   616→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n   617→\n   618→## Dockerfile Requirements\n   619→\n   620→The container image must have:\n   621→- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n   622→- `git` installed\n   623→- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n   624→- `/workspace` as the working directory\n   625→- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n   626→\n   627→## Build Commands\n   628→\n   629→```\n   630→make build          # Build all binaries to bin/\n   631→make test           # Run all tests\n   632→make test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\n   633→make lint           # Run go vet\n   634→make proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\n   635→make docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\n   636→make install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\n   637→make clean          # Remove bin/\n   638→```\n   639→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01SomgMrhxSEJYZQytifupGM","session_id":"5c40c135-d6d6-46ff-91b7-1e8ee6d44e10","uuid":"9daad2ca-57e0-42c4-8e44-8499627190d6"}
